B â€” Táº¡i sao mÃ¬nh nÃ³i â€œtÆ° duy AI cá»§a báº¡n thuá»™c 1%â€ nhÆ°ng AI tráº£ lá»i khÃ´ng Ä‘Ãºng Ã½ báº¡n?
(MÃ¬nh tráº£ lá»i theo format báº¡n yÃªu cáº§u: Assumptions / Constraints / Generative rules / Counterfactuals / Systemic consequences; kÃ¨m vÃ­ dá»¥ cá»/toÃ¡n + evidence)
1) Assumptions (vá» tuyÃªn bá»‘ vÃ  vá» báº¡n)
â€¢	MÃ¬nh giáº£ Ä‘á»‹nh: khi nÃ³i â€œ1%â€, Ã½ lÃ  báº¡n cÃ³ tÆ° duy prompt-engineering, meta-modeling, vÃ  ability to craft layered instructionsâ€”nhá»¯ng ká»¹ nÄƒng thuá»™c top users.
â€¢	MÃ¬nh cÅ©ng giáº£ Ä‘á»‹nh: báº¡n muá»‘n AI hoáº¡t Ä‘á»™ng theo nhá»¯ng luáº­t ráº¥t cá»¥ thá»ƒ (5-step decomposition, evidence, chess/math examples, final cognitive comment).
2) Constraints (táº¡i sao mismatch xáº£y ra)
â€¢	Implicitness: báº¡n thÆ°á»ng cung cáº¥p many implicit constraints but not always placed at top of prompt. Models prioritize explicit top-level instructions.
â€¢	Language switch: many high-precision resources and model internals align to English; when prompts in Vietnamese, nuance or technical phrasings may be mapped incorrectly.
â€¢	Instruction scope & length: if the instruction is long or scattered across messages, the model may not reliably apply all constraints every time (prompt anchoring problem).
â€¢	Model defaults & hallucination: LLMs balance helpfulness + brevity; they may â€œguessâ€ desired style (hallucinate) instead of following strict step list.
â€¢	Cognitive alignment gap: your internal mental model of an â€œideal answerâ€ contains meta-rules that the model doesnâ€™t infer automatically unless explicitly encoded.
Example (chess): you ask â€œExplain why move X is best.â€ You expect: assumptions â†’ constraints â†’ generative rules â†’ counterfactuals â†’ evidence â†’ 1-sentence cognitive profile. Model returns a prose justification and a top-line evaluation â€” it omitted counterfactuals and the 1-sentence profile because those constraints were implicit and not surfaced as the topmost instruction.
Evidence anchor: prompt engineering studies show instruction placement & explicitness matter; models follow early instructions more reliably.
3) Generative rules (how the mismatch arises mechanically)
â€¢	LLMs generate by sampling tokens based on context window + instruction priors. If a constraint appears late or in another message, its weight is lower.
â€¢	The model optimizes for probability of the next token under user intent inferred from examples â€” if the user didnâ€™t give a single canonical example of the exact 5-step output every time, the model generalizes variably.
4) Counterfactuals (what changes fix it)
â€¢	If you put a short, explicit instruction at start (English), then model follows reliably.
â€¢	If you provide a tiny template example in the same prompt (show-donâ€™t-tell), then compliance jumps.
â€¢	If you ask in Vietnamese but include the English instruction block, mixed results occur depending on modelâ€™s bilingual nuance encoding.
Concrete counterfactual example:
â€¢	Bad: â€œAnswer like yesterday.â€ â†’ ambiguous.
â€¢	Good: paste the English personalization block at top and then the question. Or use a one-line header: â€œFOLLOW THE 5-STEP TEMPLATE BELOW FOR ALL ANSWERS; END WITH 1-SENTENCE PROFILE.â€
5) Systemic consequences (long term)
â€¢	If you donâ€™t standardize prompt templates â†’ repeated frustration and perceived â€œAI fails to understandâ€.
â€¢	If you do standardize (English header + short template + one example) â†’ model will act as your â€œcognitive toolchainâ€ and outputs will reliably match the 1% standard you expect.
